passages.text: We review our China Software coverage based on 2Q25 performance and update our estimates to reflect our latest views. In 1H25, the avg. revenue growth of our coverage was at \(9\%\) YoY, and avg. net margin was \(- 3\%\) due to weak seasonality of the first half, while we see software companies' productivity improvement has started to reflect on margin improvement. Kingsoft Office/Thundersoft/ Sensetime revenues in 2Q25/1H25 beat on increasing AI spending, and Glodon/ Sangfor NI in 2Q was better- than- expected on improving employee productivity. We see ERP suppliers (Yonyou/ Kingdee), AI suppliers (Sensetime/ iFlytek) management are more positive on 2H25 revenue growth driven by growing demand on AI features and cloud platform with data services, meanwhile expanding new products (AI agents, edge devices empowered by AI etc.).

Post 2Q result, we see companies focusing on (1) monetization on AI tools that provide value- added features to address clients' demand; (2) diversification to overseas or new categories to offset slower IT spending in specific segments; and (3) integration of AI and core software products to capture clients' wallet share. On valuation, we see the avg. P/E of China software names was up to \(55x - 60x\) (vs. avg. at \(59x\) ) on early signs of AI monetization, and avg. EV/Sales was up to \(8x - 9x\) (vs. avg. at \(11x\) ), while still lower than 2020- 21 EV/Sales of \(12x - 18x\) . We are positive on software companies' re- rating ahead on rising AI revenues and migration to subscription business.
Maintain Buy on Empyrean/ Kingdee, Neutral on Yonyou, and Sell on ZWSOFT/ Thundersoft/ Glodon/ Sangfor. Read more: Sensetime initiation; China Software AI monetization.

Yonyou reported 2Q25 results that were overall in line with guidance, with net loss narrowed to Rmb209m and revenue growth recovered to \(7\%\) YoY (vs. 1Q25 at -21% YoY), supported by SMB growth and large- scale clients' recovery in 2Q. The mid- scale enterprise cloud revenues slowed in 1H25, and management attributed it to company's migration to a subscription model after Chanjet's transformation. The contract growth was up \(18\%\) YoY in 2Q25, and YonBIP AI orders value reached Rmb320m. Management notes the total number of employees was down to 19k by end of 2Q25 (vs. 21k by end- 2024), and expects the headcount to stay stable ahead with improving productivity. Maintain Neutral.
Exhibit 4: SMB revenues growth in 1H outperformed other segmentsYonvou revenue growth by segment in 1H25
Source: Company data
Exhibit 5:Yonvou 2Q25 result snapshot
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Earnings revision: We factor in Yonvou 2Q25 result, revise down 2025 net loss to Rmb594m (vs. previously at Rmb517m), and revise down 2026/27E earnings by \(8\%\) / \(8\%\) . We lower revenues of mid- scale enterprise cloud business to reflect lower revenues during transformation, while expect mix upgrade towards subscription. We revise up Opex ratio by 0.4ppts/ 0.2ppts in 2026/27E given the efficiency improvement still takes time.
Exhibit 6:Yonvou earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We are Neutral- rated on Yonvou with a 12- month target price of Rmb17.19(vs. previously at Rmb16.16) based on 106x 2026E target P/E (vs. previously at 88x 2026E P/E) which is based on the updated correlation between peers' 2026E trading P/E vs. 2027E earnings and OPM, with higher multiple on rising expectation on integration of AI and software solutions.
Glodon: Construction- mgmt. software recovery while slow- down of cost software; AI

tools and infrastructure solution as new driversGlodon 2Q25 revenue growth remained weak at - 5% YoY, due to a slow down in the construction- cost business amid a challenging environment, and a gradual recovery in the construction- mgmt. business. Net margin in 2Q recovered to 13% (vs. 11%/- 2% in 2Q24/1Q25) on product mix upgrade and company's cost management. Despite the real estate market weighing on the construction of new projects, management views infrastructure solutions, AI tools (Rmb40m orders on hand), and overseas business (Asia/ Europe) as key growth drivers ahead, along with improving profitability. Maintain Sell.
Exhibit 7: Glodon overseas and construction-mgmt. software outperformed Glodon 1H25 revenues growth by segment
Source: Company data
Exhibit 8: Glodon contract liabilities in 2Q down from 4Q24
Source: Company data

Earnings revision: We factor in Glodon 2Q25 result and revise down revenue by 1%- 3% in 2025- 28E on weaker- than- expected construction cost business. We revise up earnings by 18% / 12% / 2% / 1% in 2025- 28E on lower Opex ratio driven by improving employee productivity and company's cost management.
Exhibit 9:Glodon earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We are Sell- rated on Glodon with a 12- month target price of Rmb12.2 (vs. previously at Rmb11.9) based on 31x 2026E target P/E (vs. previously at 33x), which is derived from lower earnings growth in 2027E and refreshed peers correlation of PEG&M (peers group and methodology unchanged). Our target P/E multiple at 31x is between company's avg. - 1 std P/E at 28x and avg. P/E at 63x since Jan 2018.

Thundersoft: IoT and smart auto solution to drive growth ahead; 2Q25 missedThundersoft 2Q25 revenue was up \(50\%\) YoY / \(25\%\) QoQ to Rmb 1.8bn, driven by AloT business's strong growth at \(136\%\) YoY. GM showed YoY / QoQ decline in 2Q25, mainly on the GM decline of the IoT business in 1H25. With the higher operational efficiency and higher tax rate in 2Q vs. 1Q, NI in 2Q25 was up \(384\%\) YoY / - \(29\%\) QoQ to Rmb66m. Overall, management expects IoT and smart automobile to be the key drivers for the company in the following years, and the company will focus more on technology development and gaining market share, supporting the company's revenue growth ahead.
Exhibit 10: Thundersoft's 1H25 revenues growth by segments
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
Exhibit 11:Thundersoft 2Q25 result snapshot

Earnings revision: We factor in Thundersoft's 2Q25 result and revise up our 2025- 27E revenues by \(8\%\) / \(5\%\) / \(4\%\) on higher revenues of IoT business with Gen- AI features. 2025- 27E GMs are revised down to reflect lower GMs for IoT business, given that Thundersoft will focus more on market share gains. With the higher than expected operational efficiency in 2Q25, we revise down our 2025- 27E apex ratio, leading our 2025- 27E net incomes up \(0\%\) / \(1\%\) / \(1\%\) .
Exhibit 12: Earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We continue to use near- term P/E to derive our 12M target price. We update our 2026E target P/E to \(36.6x\) , which is still derived from the correlation between P/E and net income growth of peers. With the updated target multiple and earnings, our 12M target price is updated to Rmb52.4 (vs. Rmb46.0 previously). Our new TP implied P/E is at \(36.6x\) , which is around the company's avg. - 1std 12M forward P/E at 35x since 2018 and current trading P/E at 55x, suggesting that the valuation is stretched.

ZWSOFT delivered 2Q25 revenue growth at \(11\%\) YoY (vs. 1Q25 at \(5\%\) YoY), overall in line with our estimate, and we attribute muted growth in 1H to slower 3D CAD software growth at \(3\%\) YoY, lagging 2D CAD software revenues at \(12\%\) YoY in 1H. Overseas market remains strong in 1H at \(42\%\) YoY, while China market revenues were down \(5\%\) YoY, due to weak education CAD revenues which were down \(36\%\) YoY. The company launched a new generation of products (ZWCAD 2026/ZW3D 2026) in May, highlighting upgrades of ZW3D software across (1) higher design efficiency by \(50\%\) , (2) integration of 3D/2D CAD, and (3) seamless data migration. We see the product upgrade supports the company's long- term growth, and would turn more positive when we see signs of accelerated 3D CAD development.
Exhibit 15:ZWS0FT 2025 result snapshot
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Earnings revision: We factor in ZWSOFT 2Q25 results and revise down earnings by \(4\% /3\% /1\%\) in 2025- 27E on lower GM on product mix changes towards BoChao solution carrying lower GM and higher Opex ratio for new products development.
Exhibit 16:Earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We continue to derive a 12M TP from near- term P/E. We are Sell- rated on ZWSOFT with a 12- month target price of Rmb50.60 (vs. previously at Rmb48.14) based on 35.0x 2026E target P/E (vs. previously at 32.5x 2026E P/E) which is based on the updated correlation between peers' 2026E trading P/E vs. 2027E earnings and OPM.

Sangfor: Sangfor 2Q revenues growth was down to \(4\%\) YoY (vs. 1Q25 at \(22\%\) YoY), while NI in 2Q turned positive on margin improvement and improving efficiency. We view cloud computing was a key growth driver at \(26\%\) YoY in 1H25, with GM improved by 3.5ppts to \(46\%\) , while security software business remained weak at \(3\%\) YoY in 1H. We see Sangfor continues to expand its cloud computing product, supporting rising revenues contribution. The company launched AICP (Artificial Intelligence Computility Platform) in 1H25 based on its HCI solution, supporting SMB clients (enterprises, school, hospital etc.) to deploy AI models (DeepSeek, Qwen, LLAMA) with lower cost. We are positive on the company's diversification to cloud and AI business, while we believe the recovery of the security software business will still take time.

Earnings revision: We factor in Sangfor 2Q25 results and revise down revenues by \(9\% /\) \(2\% /1\%\) in 2025- 27E on lower security software revenues. GM was lowered by 0.6ppts/ 1.3ppts/ 1.6ppts in 2025- 27E due to product mix changes, and we lower Opex ratio to reflect improving employee productivity.
Exhibit 17: Earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We continue to derive a 12M TP from a near- term P/E. We are Sell- rated on Sangfor with a 12- month target price of Rmb79.0 (vs. previously at Rmb69.3) based on \(43\times 2026E\) target P/E (vs. previously at \(39\times 2026E\) P/E), which is derived from refreshed peers' correlation between P/E and NI YoY. Sangfor's target P/E multiple is lower than company's avg. 12M forward P/E at 70x since Mar 2021 and current trading P/E at \(81x\) showing that the valuation is stretched.
Key upside risks: 1) Stronger-than- expected SME client demand; 2) Higher- than- expected gross margins; and 3) Less competition in the security software market.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.

Being assigned a Buy or Sell on an Investment List is determined by a stock's total return potential relative to its coverage universe. Any stock not assigned as a Buy or a Sell on an Investment List with an active rating (i.e., a stock that is not Rating Suspended, Not Rated, Early- Stage Biotech, Coverage Suspended or Not Covered), is deemed Neutral. Each region manages Regional Conviction Lists, which are selected from Buy rated stocks on the respective region's

Investment Lists and represent investment recommendations focused on the size of the total return potential and/or the likelihood of the realization of the return across their respective areas of coverage. The addition or removal of stocks from such Conviction Lists are managed by the Investment Review Committee or other designated committee in each respective region and do not represent a change in the analysts' investment rating for such stocks.

Total return potential represents the upside or downside differential between the current share price and the price target, including all paid or anticipated dividends, expected during the time horizon associated with the price target. Price targets are required for all covered stocks. The total return potential, price target and associated time horizon are stated in each report adding or reiterating an Investment List membership.
